# SOLID Principles (Pragmatic Defaults)

- Apply SOLID to reduce change risk and keep systems easy to evolve; avoid abstraction for its own sake.

## SRP: Single Responsibility Principle

- Give each module/function/service one primary reason to change.
- Split mixed concerns (validation, orchestration, persistence, formatting) into focused units.

## OCP: Open/Closed Principle

- Keep trusted core flows stable; add variation through explicit extension seams.
- Introduce extension patterns (strategies/handlers/adapters) only when change is recurring and real.

## LSP: Liskov Substitution Principle

- Treat contracts as behavioral promises, not just type signatures.
- Substitutable implementations must preserve expected inputs, outputs, errors, side effects, and performance envelope.

## ISP: Interface Segregation Principle

- Prefer small, capability-focused interfaces/contracts.
- Do not force clients to depend on methods/fields they do not use.

## DIP: Dependency Inversion Principle

- Keep high-level policy dependent on abstractions (ports/contracts), not concrete infra/framework code.
- Inject concrete adapters at boundaries so core logic remains replaceable and testable.

## Practical Guardrails

- Start simple; add abstraction only with clear change pressure or testability benefit.
- If callers need implementation-specific conditionals, revisit contract boundaries.
